 In Java, comparing strings using the == operator and the .equals() method have different behaviors.

The == operator compares the memory addresses of the two string objects, meaning it checks if both strings are the same object in memory. This approach is not recommended for string comparison, as it may lead to unexpected results.

On the other hand, the .equals() method compares the actual content of the strings, meaning it checks if the characters in both strings are the same. This is the recommended way to compare strings in Java.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```java
String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = new String("Hello");

// Using == operator
boolean result1 = (str1 == str2); // false, as str1 and str2 are different objects in memory

// Using .equals() method
boolean result2 = str1.equals(str2); // true, as the content of str1 and str2 is the same
```

In summary, you should use the .equals() method to compare strings in Java, as it compares the actual content of the strings. The == operator should be used to compare primitive data types (e.g., int, char, boolean) or to check if two object references point to the same object in memory.

